Idem Actus, si fiat ad sublevandam prox- imi indigentiam, est quidem hactenus bonus, quod et sit de ‘materia licita, et fiat intentione recta, adeoque habeat utram- que illam de quibus jam diximus bonitatem, Oby'ecti sc. et Finis : non tamen adhuc dici potest simpliciter bonus, nisi fuerit insuper debite (ut loquuntur) circumstantionatus. Re- quiritur enim ad complementum boni operis, ultra bonitatem illam quae est ex parte objecti, et illam quae est ex parte Finis, tertia etiam bonitas ex parte Circumstantiarum. Unde dici solet, bonitatem aetus pendere ea* circumstantiis: non primario et principaliter 3. sed ultimate et completive ; suppo- sitis nimirum bonitate Objecti, et bonitate Finis. Cum ergo ad bonitatem cujuslibet actus moralis tria haec requirantur, idque conjunctim, Materia licita, Intentio recta, et debitae Circumstantioe ; manifestum est rectam intentionem per se solam non sufficere: et ex consequenti non posse bona con- scientia fieri quidquam, quacunque tandem intentione fiat, quod aut ex se ratione Objecti illicitum est, aut redditur ex Circumstantiis vitiosum.

Whence also it is often said that the goodness of an act depends on the circumstances, not primarily and principally, but ultimately and as a condition of its completeness3 supposing the goodness of the Matter and of the End.

And thus these three conditions being required for the goodness of an Act,—lawful Matter, right Intention, and due circumstances 3 it is plain that right Intention of itself does not suffice: and nothing can be done with a good Conscience, with whatever Intention, which is, by reason of the Matter, unlawful, or vitiated by the Circumstances.
